Load libraries

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)

Load cleaned data set

The cleaned datset is saved as an RData file in the data folder (i.e.df.rds) and contains a cleaned dataset of NYC yellow cab data from the months of March, June, and November in 2017.

The dataExploration.rmd file details the cleaning and processing steps, which includes: * combining the datafiles from each month, * checking for missing values, * reconfirming the observed values make sense, and * removing variables and observations not relevant to our analysis.

The data is downloaded and accessed here: NYC Taxi & Limousine Commission - Trip Record Data The Data Dictionary details the variables and its values.

my_data <- readRDS("data/df.rds")

Quick Visualizations and Summaries of Variables

Overall Average Tips Received

avg_tip <- my_data %>% summarise(average_tip=mean(tip_amount))
avg_tip
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   average_tip
##         <dbl>
## 1        1.87

Average Tips Received by Vendor Taxi Reports

vcount <- my_data %>% group_by(VendorID) %>% count() %>% as.data.frame()
vtip <- my_data %>% group_by(VendorID) %>% summarise(average_tip=mean(tip_amount)) %>% as.data.frame()
vendor <- left_join(vcount,vtip,by="VendorID")
vendor
##   VendorID        n average_tip
## 1        1 13195819    1.831776
## 2        2 15924335    1.909746

There are more taxi reports from vendor 2=VeriFone Inc. The average tip amounts are higher in the reports by vendor 2=VeriFone Inc.

Average Tips Received by Payment Type

Payment Id Payment Type
1 Credit card
2 Cash
3 No charge
4 Dispute
5 Westchester
6 Unknown 
paycount <- my_data %>% group_by(payment_type) %>% count() %>% as.data.frame()
paytip <- my_data %>% group_by(payment_type) %>% summarise(average_tip=mean(tip_amount)) %>% as.data.frame()
paytype <- left_join(paycount,paytip,by="payment_type")
paytype
##   payment_type        n   average_tip
## 1            1 19768477  2.761139e+00
## 2            2  9155558  7.536406e-07
## 3            3   152817 -2.037404e-03
## 4            4    43301  1.288654e-04
## 5            5        1  0.000000e+00
ggplot(data=paytype)+geom_point(aes(x=as.factor(payment_type),y=average_tip,size=n,color=n))+ggtitle("Average Tips Received By Payment Type")+geom_text(aes(x=as.factor(payment_type),y=average_tip,label = round(average_tip,5)), vjust = -.5)

Its a bit unclear where the negative average tip comes from, which only relates to no charge payment types. Lets visually look at the distribution of payment types.

ggplot(data=paytype, aes(x=as.factor(payment_type), y=as.numeric(n),fill=as.factor(payment_type)))+geom_bar(stat="identity")+ggtitle("Trips by Payment Type")+geom_text(aes(label = n), vjust = -.5)+scale_fill_discrete(
    name="Payment Type",
    breaks=c("1", "2", "3", "4", "5"),
    labels=c("1=Credit card","2=Cash","3=No charge","4=Dispute or Westchester","5=Unknown"))

Most payments are made by credit card and then cash. However, it looks like credit cards have the highest average tips (i.e.2.76) while all other payment types are close to 0 average tips.

Taxi Trips by Count of Passengers

pcount <- my_data %>% group_by(passenger_count) %>% count() %>% as.data.frame()
ptip <- my_data %>% group_by(passenger_count) %>% summarise(average_tip=mean(tip_amount)) %>% as.data.frame()
pass <- left_join(pcount,ptip,by="passenger_count")
pass
##   passenger_count        n average_tip
## 1               1 20915936    1.879624
## 2               2  4210325    1.885726
## 3               3  1202357    1.794119
## 4               4   557433    1.692082
## 5               5  1384630    1.899166
## 6               6   849232    1.881699
## 7               7       88    4.690227
## 8               8       87    7.823333
## 9               9       66    7.267273
ggplot(data=pass)+geom_point(aes(x=as.factor(passenger_count),y=average_tip,size=n,color=n))+ggtitle("Average Tips Received By Passenger Count")+geom_text(aes(x=as.factor(passenger_count),y=average_tip,label = round(average_tip,5)), vjust = -.5)

N describes the n size of the passenger_counts. The graph uses a scaled color and point size to compare the n sizes between the different passenger_counts. Most often taxi trips have one passenger and least often taxi trips have more than 6 passengers. However, the average tips received are greater when trips have more than 6 passengers.

Taxi Trip Records by Stored and Forwarded Data

stofor <- my_data %>% group_by(store_and_fwd_flag) %>% count() %>% as.data.frame()
ggplot(data=stofor, aes(x=as.factor(store_and_fwd_flag), y=as.numeric(n),fill=as.factor(store_and_fwd_flag)))+geom_bar(stat="identity")+ggtitle("Taxi Trips by Stored and Forwarded Data")+geom_text(aes(label = n), vjust = -.5)+guides(fill=FALSE)

The majority of taxi trip records are forwarded, and not stored in vehicle memory prior to being forwarded. Most taxi trips have connection to the server to forward and send data.

Taxi Trips by RateCodeID

Payment Id Payment Type
1 Standard rate
2 JFK
3 Newark
4 Nassau or Westchester
5 Negotiated fare
6 Group ride 
codeid <- my_data %>% group_by(RatecodeID) %>% count() %>% as.data.frame()
codetip <- my_data %>% group_by(RatecodeID) %>% summarise(average_tip=mean(tip_amount)) %>% as.data.frame()
code <- left_join(codeid,codetip,by="RatecodeID")
code
##   RatecodeID        n average_tip
## 1          1 28295446    1.705251
## 2          2   650880    7.478971
## 3          3    61738   10.698136
## 4          4    15441    8.170572
## 5          5    96409    7.026147
## 6          6      240    1.823542
ggplot(data=code)+geom_point(aes(x=as.factor(RatecodeID),y=average_tip,size=n,color=n))+ggtitle("Average Tips Received By Rate Code Type")+geom_text(aes(x=as.factor(RatecodeID),y=average_tip,label = round(average_tip,5)), vjust = -.5)

Trips with rate codes of Newark, Nassau or Westchester, JFK, and Negotiated Fare receive the highest tips on average (in that order).

Trip Distances

average_distance <- my_data%>%group_by(RatecodeID)%>%summarise(average_distance=mean(trip_distance))
code <- left_join(code,average_distance,by="RatecodeID")
code
##   RatecodeID        n average_tip average_distance

## 4          4    15441    8.170572        18.036348
## 5          5    96409    7.026147         6.321651
## 6          6      240    1.823542         1.237000

The type of rate codes that receive the highest tips on average (i.e.Newark, Nassau or Westchester, JFK, and Negotiated Fare) are the trips with the greatest average_distances.
